WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:07.210 --> 00:00:09.820
MALE SPEAKER: Good morning
and welcome to Talks at Google

00:00:09.820 --> 00:00:11.880
in Cambridge, Massachusetts.

00:00:11.880 --> 00:00:16.110
Today it is my great pleasure
to introduce Dr. Anna

00:00:16.110 --> 00:00:19.870
Frebel of Massachusetts
Institute of Technology

00:00:19.870 --> 00:00:23.370
where she is Assistant Professor
in the Department of Physics.

00:00:23.370 --> 00:00:26.280
She is here today to
discuss her book "Searching

00:00:26.280 --> 00:00:28.880
for the Older Stars--
Ancient Relics

00:00:28.880 --> 00:00:31.070
From the Early Universe."

00:00:31.070 --> 00:00:32.189
Why do we care?

00:00:32.189 --> 00:00:35.770
Because if it's not lithium,
hydrogen, or helium,

00:00:35.770 --> 00:00:37.680
it came from these stars.

00:00:37.680 --> 00:00:40.610
Dr. Frebel herself,
along with colleagues,

00:00:40.610 --> 00:00:44.510
is responsible for discovering
many of these stars.

00:00:44.510 --> 00:00:47.340
And in her book she
discovers the process

00:00:47.340 --> 00:00:49.080
by which she does it.

00:00:49.080 --> 00:00:53.550
The book itself is one of
the rare books in which we

00:00:53.550 --> 00:00:57.150
get a dose of actual
science in terms

00:00:57.150 --> 00:01:00.510
that both experts and lay
people can understand,

00:01:00.510 --> 00:01:03.270
as well as a great
behind the scenes

00:01:03.270 --> 00:01:07.810
look at what's involved
marathon observatory

00:01:07.810 --> 00:01:12.010
sessions to discover
the stars and map them.

00:01:12.010 --> 00:01:14.750
So without further
ado, please join me

00:01:14.750 --> 00:01:16.830
in welcoming Dr. Anna Frebel.

00:01:16.830 --> 00:01:20.197
[APPLAUSE]

00:01:24.994 --> 00:01:27.410
ANNA FREBEL: Thank you so much
for the great introduction.

00:01:27.410 --> 00:01:30.800
I'm very excited to be her
and to talk about my book.

00:01:30.800 --> 00:01:33.610
It's been in the making
for quite a while.

00:01:33.610 --> 00:01:37.340
So I'm really pleased
that it's finally out.

00:01:37.340 --> 00:01:39.141
And it really got very exciting.

00:01:41.910 --> 00:01:45.530
So I wanted to quickly introduce
and tell you a little bit what

00:01:45.530 --> 00:01:49.364
my goal was of all these years.

00:01:49.364 --> 00:01:50.780
Of course I'm a
scientist, but I'm

00:01:50.780 --> 00:01:55.110
very interested in
conveying my research

00:01:55.110 --> 00:02:00.870
results, but also the scientific
method to the wider audience.

00:02:00.870 --> 00:02:03.680
And in this case, I
have to quote my mom,

00:02:03.680 --> 00:02:07.580
because I regularly tell her
oh, I'm going to the telescope.

00:02:07.580 --> 00:02:08.949
I'm going observing.

00:02:08.949 --> 00:02:13.350
And she always says, yeah, yeah.

00:02:13.350 --> 00:02:15.990
Now, after having
written the book

00:02:15.990 --> 00:02:18.190
and of course her reading
it in great detail,

00:02:18.190 --> 00:02:20.670
she really understands
what this means.

00:02:20.670 --> 00:02:23.510
And the point of this is
that the public really

00:02:23.510 --> 00:02:27.090
doesn't know what
scientists do all day long.

00:02:27.090 --> 00:02:29.710
And this thing of going
observing and using telescopes

00:02:29.710 --> 00:02:31.890
is certainly very
mysterious to anyone who

00:02:31.890 --> 00:02:33.540
hasn't been at the telescope.

00:02:33.540 --> 00:02:36.060
And there are even lots
of astronomers who haven't

00:02:36.060 --> 00:02:37.365
been at a big telescope.

00:02:37.365 --> 00:02:41.110
So this is really
a widespread issue.

00:02:41.110 --> 00:02:45.260
And so I wanted to
write a book that is not

00:02:45.260 --> 00:02:47.820
your typical popular
science book that presents

00:02:47.820 --> 00:02:50.190
just the scientific results.

00:02:50.190 --> 00:02:56.330
But I also wanted to tell the
story of how we get there.

00:02:56.330 --> 00:02:59.840
As it turns out, it's never
really a straight line path.

00:02:59.840 --> 00:03:06.670
And so the big windy
road is characterized

00:03:06.670 --> 00:03:11.260
by good luck and bad luck, and
many other interesting things.

00:03:11.260 --> 00:03:16.300
And so I have devoted several
chapters to that journey.

00:03:16.300 --> 00:03:20.460
And so my motto is the journey
is the destination because I

00:03:20.460 --> 00:03:23.150
became a scientist because
I wanted to find things out

00:03:23.150 --> 00:03:26.601
and not necessarily to have
the flashiest of results.

00:03:26.601 --> 00:03:28.600
Obviously that's really
great when that happens.

00:03:28.600 --> 00:03:32.750
And it's a part of the
journey, the destination.

00:03:32.750 --> 00:03:39.890
But really what I do on a daily
basis is not all that flashy.

00:03:39.890 --> 00:03:42.490
But it's nevertheless
really interesting.

00:03:42.490 --> 00:03:45.830
And so I want to give
a realistic insight

00:03:45.830 --> 00:03:51.200
into what astronomers
do on a daily basis.

00:03:51.200 --> 00:03:54.270
So let's get the story started.

00:03:54.270 --> 00:03:56.120
Let's start right
at the beginning

00:03:56.120 --> 00:03:57.915
some 14 billion years ago.

00:04:03.930 --> 00:04:07.900
So the Big Bang occurred
some 14 billion years ago.

00:04:07.900 --> 00:04:10.700
And the universe at
that time consisted

00:04:10.700 --> 00:04:14.910
of just three elements--
hydrogen, helium, and lithium.

00:04:14.910 --> 00:04:21.690
And from that primordial gas,
the very first stars emerged.

00:04:21.690 --> 00:04:24.730
And they were made from
hydrogen, helium, and lithium,

00:04:24.730 --> 00:04:26.230
and nothing else.

00:04:26.230 --> 00:04:28.380
Now these stars had
very short lives

00:04:28.380 --> 00:04:32.802
because they have
a very high mass.

00:04:32.802 --> 00:04:35.530
I'll touch on that a
little bit later again.

00:04:35.530 --> 00:04:37.160
So they were short lived.

00:04:37.160 --> 00:04:40.960
And when they exploded
as gigantic supernovae,

00:04:40.960 --> 00:04:43.110
the elements that they
had been cooking up,

00:04:43.110 --> 00:04:45.440
the additional elements that
they had been cooking up

00:04:45.440 --> 00:04:48.010
in their cores to
sustain their luminosity,

00:04:48.010 --> 00:04:50.990
to shine, even for
their short lives,

00:04:50.990 --> 00:04:53.880
they were expelled into
the interstellar medium,

00:04:53.880 --> 00:04:55.930
into the universe.

00:04:55.930 --> 00:04:59.250
And that changed everything
because now the universe

00:04:59.250 --> 00:05:02.160
consisted not just of hydrogen
and helium and lithium,

00:05:02.160 --> 00:05:06.370
but also of elements like
carbon and oxygen and iron.

00:05:06.370 --> 00:05:08.880
And that has a whole
lot of ramifications

00:05:08.880 --> 00:05:12.250
for additional star formation
and also for galaxy formation.

00:05:12.250 --> 00:05:16.400
So clearly these stars ushered
in a new era in the universe.

00:05:16.400 --> 00:05:18.780
And then star and
galaxy formation indeed

00:05:18.780 --> 00:05:21.470
had a chance to take off.

00:05:21.470 --> 00:05:24.970
So we have this slightly
enriched material here.

00:05:24.970 --> 00:05:29.340
And from that the next
generations of stars formed.

00:05:29.340 --> 00:05:33.380
And it's actually those
early generations-- here

00:05:33.380 --> 00:05:36.780
the second one in
particular that we

00:05:36.780 --> 00:05:41.810
are trying to find-- because
these stars here now,

00:05:41.810 --> 00:05:44.300
or some of these stars
in that generation

00:05:44.300 --> 00:05:47.690
included low mass stars,
small, little stars.

00:05:47.690 --> 00:05:50.290
And they have a
very long lifetime.

00:05:50.290 --> 00:05:52.960
So they are still around today.

00:05:52.960 --> 00:05:55.130
And those are the guys
that we are hunting down

00:05:55.130 --> 00:05:57.890
with our big telescopes.

00:05:57.890 --> 00:06:00.700
So I want to tell you
more about how we do that

00:06:00.700 --> 00:06:04.680
and what we learn from
finding these stars.

00:06:04.680 --> 00:06:08.050
But first let's talk a little
bit about chemical evolution.

00:06:08.050 --> 00:06:12.530
That is the successive
buildup of heavy elements--

00:06:12.530 --> 00:06:15.860
heavier than hydrogen, helium,
lithium-- in the universe

00:06:15.860 --> 00:06:18.600
over billions of years.

00:06:18.600 --> 00:06:22.880
Imagine that this here is
the primordial gas cloud,

00:06:22.880 --> 00:06:25.760
so just what was there
after the Big Bang.

00:06:25.760 --> 00:06:28.170
And the very first stars formed.

00:06:28.170 --> 00:06:29.100
And they evolved.

00:06:29.100 --> 00:06:31.250
And they exploded as supernovae.

00:06:31.250 --> 00:06:33.410
And so the elements
that they cooked up

00:06:33.410 --> 00:06:35.750
inside their cores
for energy production,

00:06:35.750 --> 00:06:39.030
they got ejected back
into the reservoir here.

00:06:39.030 --> 00:06:40.700
Then this is enriched
a little bit.

00:06:40.700 --> 00:06:42.620
You form the next
generation of stars.

00:06:42.620 --> 00:06:45.330
And then it goes round
and round and round.

00:06:45.330 --> 00:06:49.950
And there are
several consequences.

00:06:49.950 --> 00:06:53.860
You can immediately see that
you have this cycle here only

00:06:53.860 --> 00:06:56.765
go around only a few times
as opposed to a few hundred

00:06:56.765 --> 00:07:00.020
or thousand times,
that the amount

00:07:00.020 --> 00:07:04.410
of the heavy elements in the
resulting stars will increase.

00:07:04.410 --> 00:07:10.020
So older stars contain
much fewer of the elements.

00:07:10.020 --> 00:07:12.120
And the younger
ones contain more.

00:07:12.120 --> 00:07:16.440
And the sun, for reference,
also formed at some point,

00:07:16.440 --> 00:07:20.090
probably when the cycle had gone
around maybe a thousand times

00:07:20.090 --> 00:07:23.860
in this local region where
the sun formed later.

00:07:26.840 --> 00:07:30.040
And the sun contains-- I'll
have another slide on that--

00:07:30.040 --> 00:07:34.440
contains a whole 1.4%
of the heavy elements.

00:07:34.440 --> 00:07:36.200
So that's already a lot.

00:07:36.200 --> 00:07:40.010
But I'll say a little bit
more about this in a second.

00:07:40.010 --> 00:07:45.300
So our primary goal is, when
we search for the oldest stars,

00:07:45.300 --> 00:07:47.450
is to look for the
stars with the least

00:07:47.450 --> 00:07:50.850
amount of heavy elements in
them because as it turns out,

00:07:50.850 --> 00:07:53.710
it's incredibly difficult
to actually obtain

00:07:53.710 --> 00:07:56.170
an actual age for the star.

00:07:56.170 --> 00:07:58.820
However, at the very end,
I'll show you one example

00:07:58.820 --> 00:08:01.040
where we managed to do that.

00:08:01.040 --> 00:08:03.768
So that kind of
wraps it all up nice.

00:08:07.220 --> 00:08:10.920
So we have to talk about
stellar chemical compositions.

00:08:10.920 --> 00:08:14.720
And for reference
here I have at the top

00:08:14.720 --> 00:08:17.640
the composition of the
universe after the Big Bang.

00:08:17.640 --> 00:08:19.170
I've already mentioned this.

00:08:19.170 --> 00:08:24.160
We have hydrogen, 75%, 25%,
and just a tiny sprinkle

00:08:24.160 --> 00:08:24.720
of lithium.

00:08:24.720 --> 00:08:27.280
So I excluded that
because actually it's

00:08:27.280 --> 00:08:30.430
not too relevant for the
remainder of my talk.

00:08:30.430 --> 00:08:34.539
And then after about 9 billion
years of chemical evolution,

00:08:34.539 --> 00:08:36.690
the sun formed.

00:08:36.690 --> 00:08:39.580
That was about 4.6
billion years ago.

00:08:39.580 --> 00:08:41.700
And you can see how the
composition changed.

00:08:41.700 --> 00:08:44.240
Hydrogen got convert
it into helium,

00:08:44.240 --> 00:08:47.340
and helium got converted
into heavy elements.

00:08:47.340 --> 00:08:51.740
So the sun is very
rich in heavy elements,

00:08:51.740 --> 00:08:55.890
comparatively, a whole 1.4%.

00:08:55.890 --> 00:08:57.400
And so what we're
doing is we are

00:08:57.400 --> 00:09:02.040
looking for stars that have a
million times less than this.

00:09:02.040 --> 00:09:04.110
So a whole different
ball game, but that

00:09:04.110 --> 00:09:09.480
gives you an idea of what the
ranges we're playing with.

00:09:09.480 --> 00:09:13.530
So there are a lot of chemical
elements in the periodic table.

00:09:13.530 --> 00:09:14.762
Here a few illustrated.

00:09:14.762 --> 00:09:16.470
I hope your little
coffee shop over there

00:09:16.470 --> 00:09:19.350
will soon sell element cupcakes.

00:09:19.350 --> 00:09:21.580
I'm sure they will taste
particularly sweet.

00:09:21.580 --> 00:09:23.630
They certainly would to me.

00:09:23.630 --> 00:09:30.530
A few are highlighted here, C,
N, O, P, S, and N-- oh sorry,

00:09:30.530 --> 00:09:35.460
C, N, O, P, S-- that are
the elements of life.

00:09:35.460 --> 00:09:39.030
As humans, we consist
mostly of carbon.

00:09:39.030 --> 00:09:42.090
All life forms are carbon based.

00:09:42.090 --> 00:09:46.720
And in particular, of
these five elements here.

00:09:46.720 --> 00:09:51.840
But we contain also a whole
bunch of other elements.

00:09:51.840 --> 00:09:55.660
And all that material of course
needs to come from somewhere.

00:09:55.660 --> 00:09:58.990
And I already mentioned
that stars produce

00:09:58.990 --> 00:10:01.460
elements for energy production.

00:10:01.460 --> 00:10:04.410
But one thing that
is often forgotten

00:10:04.410 --> 00:10:09.420
is that we actually also carry
a little Big Bang material in us

00:10:09.420 --> 00:10:13.170
because our bodies
consists 90% of water.

00:10:13.170 --> 00:10:16.060
And water is made of
hydrogen and oxygen.

00:10:16.060 --> 00:10:19.870
And those protons
in the hydrogen,

00:10:19.870 --> 00:10:22.130
they were certainly
recycled through stars.

00:10:22.130 --> 00:10:24.820
But they were made
in the Big Bang.

00:10:24.820 --> 00:10:27.180
And so we're not just
children of the stars,

00:10:27.180 --> 00:10:28.670
but also children
of the Big Bang.

00:10:28.670 --> 00:10:30.350
And so I think
that's really nice

00:10:30.350 --> 00:10:34.110
that we can feel a little
connected to the beginning.

00:10:37.360 --> 00:10:42.370
And so I already mentioned
here just a few pretty pictures

00:10:42.370 --> 00:10:44.700
because in every
astronomy talk, you also

00:10:44.700 --> 00:10:46.400
need a few pretty pictures.

00:10:46.400 --> 00:10:50.120
This is a star
forming region here.

00:10:50.120 --> 00:10:52.400
But the elements are
not just made in stars.

00:10:52.400 --> 00:10:55.130
They're also made in
supernova explosions.

00:10:55.130 --> 00:10:58.720
Here are a few examples of
various so-called supernova

00:10:58.720 --> 00:11:00.780
remnants.

00:11:00.780 --> 00:11:06.450
So they are just the shells
of heavy element material

00:11:06.450 --> 00:11:10.420
that are still expanding
since the explosion.

00:11:10.420 --> 00:11:13.390
And you can actually see in
the different colors here,

00:11:13.390 --> 00:11:15.770
they are depicting
different elements.

00:11:15.770 --> 00:11:18.760
So you can literally witness
how these new elements that

00:11:18.760 --> 00:11:21.050
are produced in stars
and supernova explosions

00:11:21.050 --> 00:11:23.952
are being dispersed
into the cosmos.

00:11:27.520 --> 00:11:30.070
Here is another version
of the periodic table.

00:11:30.070 --> 00:11:32.760
You can see that
I'm ready for lunch,

00:11:32.760 --> 00:11:38.590
because I like somewhat
unusual depictions

00:11:38.590 --> 00:11:40.830
of the periodic table
of the elements.

00:11:40.830 --> 00:11:44.500
But then I'm also not a
chemist, I'm an astronomer.

00:11:44.500 --> 00:11:47.150
We take a unique spin
on the periodic table

00:11:47.150 --> 00:11:49.910
because you probably know
from your chemistry classes

00:11:49.910 --> 00:11:55.490
that in chemistry here,
according to the colors,

00:11:55.490 --> 00:11:57.620
the columns are very
important in chemistry

00:11:57.620 --> 00:12:02.010
because the elements in a
column have similar properties.

00:12:02.010 --> 00:12:04.960
As an astronomer, I couldn't
care less about the columns.

00:12:04.960 --> 00:12:09.070
I care about the rows because
the elements are subsequently

00:12:09.070 --> 00:12:10.810
made.

00:12:10.810 --> 00:12:13.990
If you want to
create iron here, you

00:12:13.990 --> 00:12:16.170
have to create these
guys here beforehand.

00:12:16.170 --> 00:12:19.030
So it goes one to
one to one to one

00:12:19.030 --> 00:12:20.200
to get where you have to go.

00:12:20.200 --> 00:12:22.880
So we care for the rows.

00:12:22.880 --> 00:12:25.540
And so maybe I have
to soon bake one

00:12:25.540 --> 00:12:29.960
of those 109 cupcakes colored
in a slightly different way.

00:12:33.440 --> 00:12:35.940
Let's get to the
heart of the matter.

00:12:35.940 --> 00:12:39.130
So my work is often
called stellar archaeology

00:12:39.130 --> 00:12:43.340
because we take these survivor
stars that are in the Milky Way

00:12:43.340 --> 00:12:47.330
today, and we study their
chemical composition so that we

00:12:47.330 --> 00:12:51.460
can [INAUDIBLE] their age, or
at least their formation era,

00:12:51.460 --> 00:12:55.770
due to the small amounts
of heavy elements in them.

00:12:55.770 --> 00:12:59.770
And from that, we
can then infer what

00:12:59.770 --> 00:13:01.610
the composition
of this gas cloud

00:13:01.610 --> 00:13:04.210
was this little guy formed from.

00:13:04.210 --> 00:13:08.970
And that tells us
what exactly came out

00:13:08.970 --> 00:13:13.760
of one of those first
star supernova explosions.

00:13:13.760 --> 00:13:15.500
Because as I said
in the beginning,

00:13:15.500 --> 00:13:18.630
these guys here are very
massive and short lived.

00:13:18.630 --> 00:13:21.040
So we can actually not
study them anymore.

00:13:21.040 --> 00:13:23.790
The only way we can do this
is through this indirect way

00:13:23.790 --> 00:13:26.510
of looking at their
stellar genes that

00:13:26.510 --> 00:13:30.690
are incorporated into the
next generation of star.

00:13:30.690 --> 00:13:32.130
So obviously that
requires that we

00:13:32.130 --> 00:13:35.170
have to find these second
generation stars here.

00:13:35.170 --> 00:13:37.450
But we are finding them now.

00:13:37.450 --> 00:13:41.260
And so we can infer properties
of these very first stars

00:13:41.260 --> 00:13:44.600
that really shaped the
universe at this early time.

00:13:48.190 --> 00:13:51.300
So where do we find these stars?

00:13:51.300 --> 00:13:53.310
Let's look at the
Milky Way for a second.

00:13:53.310 --> 00:13:56.270
Here is a top view.

00:13:56.270 --> 00:13:59.230
And we live in a spiral galaxy.

00:13:59.230 --> 00:14:00.930
This is the galactic center.

00:14:00.930 --> 00:14:02.140
It's very brightly lit.

00:14:02.140 --> 00:14:04.020
You can actually see it here.

00:14:04.020 --> 00:14:06.980
This is what we see on the
sky because we sit over here

00:14:06.980 --> 00:14:08.940
about 2/3 on the way out.

00:14:08.940 --> 00:14:12.130
And in the northern
hemisphere from here,

00:14:12.130 --> 00:14:14.000
we are actually looking out.

00:14:14.000 --> 00:14:17.680
So what we see on the sky
is this spiral arm here.

00:14:17.680 --> 00:14:22.020
Whereas if we go to the
southern hemisphere,

00:14:22.020 --> 00:14:25.450
we look in that direction and
we see that spiral arm here.

00:14:25.450 --> 00:14:27.610
But it's backlit by
the galactic center.

00:14:27.610 --> 00:14:31.960
And that's why the Milky Way
is so much better in the south.

00:14:31.960 --> 00:14:33.480
And this is a
picture of the south.

00:14:33.480 --> 00:14:40.070
So you can see the back lighting
of the galactic center here.

00:14:40.070 --> 00:14:46.150
And here is a
further edge on view.

00:14:46.150 --> 00:14:48.500
What I want to focus
on now is actually

00:14:48.500 --> 00:14:52.430
not the disk itself at
all, but this outer region

00:14:52.430 --> 00:14:54.280
here that we call
the halo, which

00:14:54.280 --> 00:14:58.550
is very thinly populated
spherical envelope that

00:14:58.550 --> 00:15:02.640
kind of protects and
swirls around the disk.

