00:18:08.880 --> 00:18:11.220
But the spectroscopic
analysis has

00:18:11.220 --> 00:18:16.480
revealed that this is the by
now second most iron poor star.

00:18:16.480 --> 00:18:20.610
So this is a second generation
star in the universe.

00:18:20.610 --> 00:18:23.100
That's pretty neat I think.

00:18:23.100 --> 00:18:27.590
So let's briefly recap
what we do in terms

00:18:27.590 --> 00:18:29.740
of a chemical balance analysis.

00:18:29.740 --> 00:18:32.140
That is based on a spectrum.

00:18:32.140 --> 00:18:35.160
We collect the starlight
with a big telescope.

00:18:35.160 --> 00:18:36.540
And we have a
spectrograph, which

00:18:36.540 --> 00:18:41.190
is basically a prism here.

00:18:41.190 --> 00:18:44.727
So the prism splits up the
light into the rainbow colors,

00:18:44.727 --> 00:18:46.310
and then you get a
spectrum like that.

00:18:46.310 --> 00:18:47.893
It doesn't look quite
like the rainbow

00:18:47.893 --> 00:18:50.070
because there are all
these dark lines in here.

00:18:50.070 --> 00:18:54.860
And each dark line refers
to a little piece of light

00:18:54.860 --> 00:18:56.360
that is lost.

00:18:56.360 --> 00:18:58.650
And what's happening
in the stellar surface

00:18:58.650 --> 00:19:00.440
that we are all
observing, there are

00:19:00.440 --> 00:19:03.800
all sorts of elements,
atoms, swirling around.

00:19:03.800 --> 00:19:08.490
And each element absorbs
at certain wavelengths.

00:19:08.490 --> 00:19:11.550
And well, absorption means
that the light is absorbed.

00:19:11.550 --> 00:19:12.210
It's gone.

00:19:12.210 --> 00:19:14.860
And so that's why we
see these lines here.

00:19:14.860 --> 00:19:17.630
And actually a cross cut
through here is shown up here.

00:19:17.630 --> 00:19:21.020
You can see all of
these lines here.

00:19:21.020 --> 00:19:22.500
These are all absorption lines.

00:19:22.500 --> 00:19:26.290
And if we take a little
peek, a closer look here,

00:19:26.290 --> 00:19:28.170
we have hydrogen lines here.

00:19:28.170 --> 00:19:30.710
And here's even a
tiny calcium line.

00:19:30.710 --> 00:19:33.020
So we can measure the
strength of these lines

00:19:33.020 --> 00:19:35.660
and then infer their abundance.

00:19:35.660 --> 00:19:38.220
Because that's really what we
want in order to determine OK,

00:19:38.220 --> 00:19:40.240
how much of these heavy
elements is there,

00:19:40.240 --> 00:19:42.910
and is that a star
that could have formed

00:19:42.910 --> 00:19:45.960
as part of the second generation
because it's abundances are

00:19:45.960 --> 00:19:48.290
low.

00:19:48.290 --> 00:19:54.090
And so I already hinted at
that these stars are very rare.

00:19:54.090 --> 00:19:56.660
They formed 13
billion years ago.

00:19:56.660 --> 00:20:00.940
And since then, the universe has
been quite busy making stars.

00:20:00.940 --> 00:20:05.360
And so we need a big sky surveys
to go from hundreds-- sorry,

00:20:05.360 --> 00:20:07.710
from millions, actually
hundreds of millions almost,

00:20:07.710 --> 00:20:12.100
stars, to actual
hundreds and then dozens.

00:20:12.100 --> 00:20:14.640
And we do that by getting
different kinds of spectra.

00:20:14.640 --> 00:20:17.430
And the quality goes up and up.

00:20:17.430 --> 00:20:20.140
We really need very high
resolution spectra here

00:20:20.140 --> 00:20:21.950
which just means
we really stretch

00:20:21.950 --> 00:20:26.330
