So it took probably
several billion years

00:28:36.120 --> 00:28:42.770
before there was enough material
out there to have planets form.

00:28:42.770 --> 00:28:46.360
That sort of transition of
when the first planets emerged

00:28:46.360 --> 00:28:51.380
is currently researched, and
certainly a very, very exciting

00:28:51.380 --> 00:28:53.550
topic.

00:28:53.550 --> 00:28:56.950
And I look forward to
knowing the answer.

00:28:56.950 --> 00:29:00.230
But no planets in
the early universe.

00:29:00.230 --> 00:29:03.180
And so what do we
learn from this now?

00:29:03.180 --> 00:29:05.800
I already mentioned
many tidbits.

00:29:05.800 --> 00:29:07.710
So let's put this together.

00:29:07.710 --> 00:29:12.310
So we usually use iron, but also
elements like carbon and oxygen

00:29:12.310 --> 00:29:16.840
to try to figure out what
went on in the supernova.

00:29:16.840 --> 00:29:20.900
And we work with people who
calculate how many elements

00:29:20.900 --> 00:29:27.640
are produced by the star itself
as it does before it explodes,

00:29:27.640 --> 00:29:29.840
and then in the
supernova explosion.

00:29:29.840 --> 00:29:32.180
And we compare those models.

00:29:32.180 --> 00:29:35.570
And then we figure out oh, it
was this and this much that

00:29:35.570 --> 00:29:38.560
came out of this first star.

00:29:38.560 --> 00:29:42.710
And this really is the one
and only diagnostic tool

00:29:42.710 --> 00:29:45.950
that we have to study the
properties of the first stars.

00:29:45.950 --> 00:29:47.370
So what are we interested in?

00:29:47.370 --> 00:29:50.090
Well, first of all we're
interested in their masses,

00:29:50.090 --> 00:29:53.430
because theory has actually told
us that these first stars were

00:29:53.430 --> 00:29:54.770
very massive.

00:29:54.770 --> 00:29:56.980
It's actually very
difficult for stars

00:29:56.980 --> 00:29:59.520
to form from just hydrogen
and helium and lithium.

00:29:59.520 --> 00:30:02.920
It can't really cool down,
so it can't be a clump well.

00:30:02.920 --> 00:30:04.760
And so it's difficult
to make small stars.

00:30:04.760 --> 00:30:08.240
So we would like to confirm
that the theorists are right

00:30:08.240 --> 00:30:10.980
and that they have high
masses, maybe as [INAUDIBLE]

00:30:10.980 --> 00:30:14.510
says, maybe up to 100
solar masses, 100 times

00:30:14.510 --> 00:30:16.050
the mass of the sun.

00:30:16.050 --> 00:30:18.720
And indeed our works,
from this comparison,

00:30:18.720 --> 00:30:22.040
we have found that the first
stars might have been something

00:30:22.040 --> 00:30:24.780
like 50 or 60 solar masses.

00:30:24.780 --> 00:30:27.720
No, it's not exactly 100, but
that was just a ballpark number

00:30:27.720 --> 00:30:28.720
to start with.

00:30:28.720 --> 00:30:32.600
So it's definitely
more than 10 or 15,

00:30:32.600 --> 00:30:36.930
which is a typical mass
for today's larger stars.

00:30:36.930 --> 00:30:40.310
So kind of different back then.

00:30:40.310 --> 00:30:44.170
But we can also learn about
the explosion mechanism

00:30:44.170 --> 00:30:46.040
and the explosion energy.

00:30:46.040 --> 00:30:49.230
And that is very important
for understanding really

00:30:49.230 --> 00:30:51.660
how much power
these stars started

00:30:51.660 --> 00:30:54.090
to change the universe
when they exploded.

00:30:54.090 --> 00:30:56.630
There are all sorts
of ramifications

00:30:56.630 --> 00:30:59.410
that come from that
depending on how

00:30:59.410 --> 00:31:03.420
violently these stars exploded.

00:31:03.420 --> 00:31:06.390
So we have a whole bunch
of ongoing sky surveys

00:31:06.390 --> 00:31:09.110
that help us to find
more of these stars,

00:31:09.110 --> 00:31:13.300
especially some that
involve a new technique that

00:31:13.300 --> 00:31:15.060
is a lot more efficient now.

00:31:15.060 --> 00:31:21.560
So hopefully we'll find a
lot more of these guys soon.

00:31:21.560 --> 00:31:24.780
I think in the last
few minutes I'd

00:31:24.780 --> 00:31:27.740
like to introduce this
second star to you.

00:31:27.740 --> 00:31:31.090
Here's another fuzzy
blob in the universe.

00:31:31.090 --> 00:31:32.910
Now this one is
actually fairly bright.

00:31:32.910 --> 00:31:34.820
So if you have a small
telescope at home

00:31:34.820 --> 00:31:37.210
or you know someone who
has, you can actually

00:31:37.210 --> 00:31:39.500
take a picture yourself.

00:31:39.500 --> 00:31:43.210
This was taken by an
amateur astronomer.

00:31:43.210 --> 00:31:45.220
And he sent me
this picture there.

00:31:45.220 --> 00:31:46.580
So that's kind of nice.

00:31:46.580 --> 00:31:50.200
But again, you need that
spectroscopic knowledge

00:31:50.200 --> 00:31:53.120
to say that this is one of
older stars we know because we

00:31:53.120 --> 00:31:56.180
have measured its age.

00:31:56.180 --> 00:31:57.430
So what's the big deal here?

00:31:57.430 --> 00:32:00.380
We have taken a spectrum, and
the spectrum is very unusual

00:32:00.380 --> 00:32:03.240
because it contains
absorption lines from very

00:32:03.240 --> 00:32:07.360
heavy rare earth elements.

00:32:07.360 --> 00:32:11.630
And that included elements
like thorium and uranium.

00:32:11.630 --> 00:32:14.710
And you hopefully know that
these are radioactive elements.

00:32:14.710 --> 00:32:17.740
So as soon as you deal
with radioactive material,

00:32:17.740 --> 00:32:19.970
you have yourself a clock.

00:32:19.970 --> 00:32:22.700
So we're making use of that.

00:32:22.700 --> 00:32:27.050
And it basically works like
the radiocarbon method,

00:32:27.050 --> 00:32:30.920
just we're dealing with
slightly older [INAUDIBLE].

00:32:30.920 --> 00:32:35.030
So if you think that
this was the supernova,

00:32:35.030 --> 00:32:37.140
these heavy elements
including, thorium, uranium,

00:32:37.140 --> 00:32:38.098
they got produced here.

00:32:38.098 --> 00:32:40.100
They got expelled
into the universe.

00:32:40.100 --> 00:32:41.970
And then our little guy formed.

00:32:41.970 --> 00:32:45.380
And all this material
got baked into the star.

00:32:45.380 --> 00:32:49.310
And then actually, pretty much
since the supernova explosion,

00:32:49.310 --> 00:32:52.470
the radioactive material
has started to decay.

00:32:52.470 --> 00:32:54.740
And today we
measure what's left.

00:32:54.740 --> 00:32:56.580
And we compared that
with calculations

00:32:56.580 --> 00:32:58.530
for how much was produced.

00:32:58.530 --> 00:33:01.110
And bang, we have an age.

00:33:01.110 --> 00:33:02.650
That all sounds really easy.

00:33:02.650 --> 00:33:07.610
And the concept is
very straightforward.

00:33:07.610 --> 00:33:09.450
Before I show you
why this is so hard,

00:33:09.450 --> 00:33:12.030
let me just
illustrate to you what

00:33:12.030 --> 00:33:15.240
it means to work on some
of those special stars.

00:33:15.240 --> 00:33:18.440
So here are a few elements
that we regularly measure

00:33:18.440 --> 00:33:23.040
in all of our old stars.

00:33:23.040 --> 00:33:26.880
We then have these purple ones
here, the rare earth elements,

00:33:26.880 --> 00:33:30.250
especially the ones
here at the bottom,

00:33:30.250 --> 00:33:32.170
that we can measure in there.

00:33:32.170 --> 00:33:35.250
These elements are produced
only in supernova explosions

00:33:35.250 --> 00:33:36.990
during very, very
special conditions.

00:33:36.990 --> 00:33:39.840
So the gold and the
silver from your jewelry

00:33:39.840 --> 00:33:43.870
all comes from these very
special supernova explosions.

00:33:43.870 --> 00:33:48.190
And there are still a
lot of open questions

00:33:48.190 --> 00:33:51.320
about this process that
makes these elements.

00:33:51.320 --> 00:33:54.670
And so it's very exciting for
us to find some of these stars

00:33:54.670 --> 00:33:56.680
so we can chime
into this question

00:33:56.680 --> 00:33:59.630
where elements like silver
and gold actually come from

00:33:59.630 --> 00:34:02.940
and how exactly they are
produced in the universe.

00:34:02.940 --> 00:34:05.910
So here is why this
measurement takes

00:34:05.910 --> 00:34:08.060
an incredible amount of data.

00:34:08.060 --> 00:34:10.350
And it's a very
difficult analysis,

00:34:10.350 --> 00:34:14.179
because we want to
measure uranium abundance.

00:34:14.179 --> 00:34:18.190
And so here you have absorption
lines-- magnesium, iron,

00:34:18.190 --> 00:34:21.560
neodymium, samarium, iron here.

00:34:21.560 --> 00:34:24.000
And you see it's a
blow up [INAUDIBLE].

00:34:24.000 --> 00:34:26.580
So if you look at
this blue line,

00:34:26.580 --> 00:34:28.840
this is a synthetic
spectrum that we

00:34:28.840 --> 00:34:33.949
have created to model the
star that contains no uranium.

00:34:33.949 --> 00:34:35.860
And the question
is, does that one

00:34:35.860 --> 00:34:39.260
correspond to the observed
data, which is the dots?

00:34:39.260 --> 00:34:41.380
And clearly the answer is no.

00:34:41.380 --> 00:34:43.770
Instead we have data that's
a little bit lower, which

00:34:43.770 --> 00:34:46.920
means there is a little
uranium absorption.

00:34:46.920 --> 00:34:49.610
And so we have then
created models that kind of

00:34:49.610 --> 00:34:52.776
reproduce those here.

00:34:52.776 --> 00:34:55.190
And if the uranium
was not decaying,

00:34:55.190 --> 00:34:57.596
it would have been
absorbed up to here.

00:34:57.596 --> 00:34:58.970
So that would be
easy to measure.

00:34:58.970 --> 00:35:02.410
But it's good that it's decaying
because it gives us this clock.

00:35:02.410 --> 00:35:05.890
So making this
measurement here requires

00:35:05.890 --> 00:35:09.530
extremely exquisite data.

00:35:09.530 --> 00:35:12.170
But it worked because
this star is bright.

00:35:12.170 --> 00:35:13.460
And we got an age.

00:35:13.460 --> 00:35:15.880
Well, this is not
precision cosmology,

00:35:15.880 --> 00:35:18.710
but nevertheless it's an
important contribution

00:35:18.710 --> 00:35:22.480
to the early universe or to
studies of the early universe.

00:35:22.480 --> 00:35:26.440
And it confirms
that the whole story

00:35:26.440 --> 00:35:29.130
I have told you about
the chemical composition

00:35:29.130 --> 00:35:33.700
and they're telling us that
we can look back in time

00:35:33.700 --> 00:35:36.570
to this early era by
measuring chemical abundances

00:35:36.570 --> 00:35:38.600
is actually correct.

00:35:38.600 --> 00:35:41.330
So here are different
elements ratios.

00:35:41.330 --> 00:35:45.070
They all involve either
thorium, or uranium, or both.

00:35:45.070 --> 00:35:47.640
And these are ages
in billion years.

00:35:47.640 --> 00:35:50.600
Now the universe is
13.8 billion years.

00:35:50.600 --> 00:35:53.320
So this is just a mathematical
number that pops out.

00:35:53.320 --> 00:35:55.510
Obviously it's
unphysical, but math

00:35:55.510 --> 00:35:56.810
doesn't care about physics.

00:35:56.810 --> 00:35:59.810
So we have to take it.

00:35:59.810 --> 00:36:01.550
But if you average
all of this, it

00:36:01.550 --> 00:36:03.550
comes out to about
13 billion years.

00:36:03.550 --> 00:36:05.530
And that is the number we like.

00:36:05.530 --> 00:36:09.100
It's very consistent with
the age of the universe.

00:36:09.100 --> 00:36:14.450
Now there are some uncertainties
of course, but it is not 10,

00:36:14.450 --> 00:36:16.290
and it's not 5 billion years.

00:36:16.290 --> 00:36:17.810
It's not like the sun.

00:36:17.810 --> 00:36:22.740
And even 10 is still a
while away from 14 here.

00:36:22.740 --> 00:36:26.700
So the concept of stellar
archaeology is correct.

00:36:26.700 --> 00:36:28.490
It works.

00:36:28.490 --> 00:36:32.670
And these old stars, first
of all, they really are old.

00:36:32.670 --> 00:36:35.620
And we can use them to
explore the early universe.

00:36:35.620 --> 00:36:40.110
And of course before the
era of these satellites that

00:36:40.110 --> 00:36:44.500
probe the cosmic microwave
background radiation,

00:36:44.500 --> 00:36:48.090
and that led to the very
precise determination of the age

00:36:48.090 --> 00:36:52.610
of the universe to 13.8 billion
years, methods like these

00:36:52.610 --> 00:36:55.980
were the standard
to date the universe

00:36:55.980 --> 00:36:59.140
and to provide a lower limit
to the age of the universe.

00:36:59.140 --> 00:37:03.730
So when I went to high school,
that was still the standard.

00:37:03.730 --> 00:37:05.780
And this would have made
a great addition then.

00:37:08.410 --> 00:37:11.340
OK, so that brings
me to the end of it.

00:37:11.340 --> 00:37:15.320
I hope I could give you just a
tiny little bit of an insight

00:37:15.320 --> 00:37:18.190
that these old stars really
are like little diamonds

00:37:18.190 --> 00:37:20.690
in the sky.

00:37:20.690 --> 00:37:22.690
They are very rare.

00:37:22.690 --> 00:37:25.980
They are difficult to come
by, but we have our methods.

00:37:25.980 --> 00:37:28.320
I didn't have time to
talk much about this,

00:37:28.320 --> 00:37:31.240
but many contain actually
unusually large amounts

00:37:31.240 --> 00:37:33.520
of carbon compared to
the other elements.

00:37:33.520 --> 00:37:35.900
And that actually
indicates to us

00:37:35.900 --> 00:37:40.300
that carbon is not just an
important element for us today,

00:37:40.300 --> 00:37:43.640
since we're all carbon based,
but it was probably also

00:37:43.640 --> 00:37:47.260
the most important element that
helped in the early universe

00:37:47.260 --> 00:37:49.960
after the formation
of the first stars.

00:37:49.960 --> 00:37:52.720
So carbon really is the
most important element

00:37:52.720 --> 00:37:55.940
if you ask me at
all cosmic times.

00:37:55.940 --> 00:37:58.580
And well, these
stars are quite old.

00:37:58.580 --> 00:38:01.690
So I would say they last
almost until forever.

00:38:01.690 --> 00:38:05.880
And we can address, in theory,
many different and exciting

00:38:05.880 --> 00:38:07.220
science questions with them.

00:38:07.220 --> 00:38:10.010
So there's almost an old
star for any kind of question

00:38:10.010 --> 00:38:11.050
you might have.

00:38:11.050 --> 00:38:13.850
And of course when you find
them, they make you happy.

00:38:13.850 --> 00:38:16.590
So I would just say-- and
my slides a little cut

00:38:16.590 --> 00:38:20.120
off there-- with our
new and ongoing service

00:38:20.120 --> 00:38:21.810
and the big telescopes
that we're using,

00:38:21.810 --> 00:38:24.700
we are continuing
this treasure hunt.

00:38:24.700 --> 00:38:25.640
Thank you so much.

00:38:25.640 --> 00:38:30.041
[APPLAUSE]

