00:42:19.900 --> 00:42:23.200
because, as you said, there's
only a teeny tiny amount

00:42:23.200 --> 00:42:26.010
in this one, and there is zero
in the first generation one.

00:42:26.010 --> 00:42:29.390
So it doesn't really seem a
striking difference to me.

00:42:29.390 --> 00:42:34.550
Why is it that very teeny tiny
amount of heavier elements

00:42:34.550 --> 00:42:37.295
can make such a big difference
in the mass of forming stars?

00:42:37.295 --> 00:42:38.920
ANNA FREBEL: Thank
you for asking that,

00:42:38.920 --> 00:42:42.800
because I usually don't have
time to talk about that.

00:42:42.800 --> 00:42:45.370
So zero or little
makes a big difference

00:42:45.370 --> 00:42:49.560
because heavy elements,
especially carbon and oxygen,

00:42:49.560 --> 00:42:51.590
they act as coolants.

00:42:51.590 --> 00:42:54.350
So imagine you have this soup.

00:42:54.350 --> 00:42:57.510
And the soup just can't cool.

00:42:57.510 --> 00:43:00.870
You add just a sprinkle of
salt, well in this case,

00:43:00.870 --> 00:43:03.020
you change the whole
flavor of your soup.

00:43:03.020 --> 00:43:05.030
It goes from bland to tasty.

00:43:05.030 --> 00:43:08.540
And the same kind
of thing happens

00:43:08.540 --> 00:43:09.900
when you add a little carbon.

00:43:09.900 --> 00:43:12.480
It suddenly can cool
and it can clump.

00:43:12.480 --> 00:43:14.080
And it can fragment.

00:43:14.080 --> 00:43:17.630
And once you have
fragmentation, the cloud

00:43:17.630 --> 00:43:19.360
breaks up into smaller clumps.

00:43:19.360 --> 00:43:21.740
And then gravity will
again do its thing,

00:43:21.740 --> 00:43:25.320
but on smaller length scales.

00:43:25.320 --> 00:43:27.480
It's a little bit more
complicated than that,

00:43:27.480 --> 00:43:29.267
but that's the basic idea.

00:43:29.267 --> 00:43:31.600
So as soon as you have some
elements-- because you know,

00:43:31.600 --> 00:43:34.720
carbon is a more extended
complicated atom.

00:43:34.720 --> 00:43:38.135
So it has a lot of
transitions for the electrons.

00:43:38.135 --> 00:43:39.760
And they're just kind
of wiggling away.

00:43:39.760 --> 00:43:41.343
And carbon and oxygen
are particularly

00:43:41.343 --> 00:43:44.740
good at having so-called fine
structure line transitions.

00:43:44.740 --> 00:43:48.725
So it can wiggle, whereas
a hydrogen atom really, it

00:43:48.725 --> 00:43:49.350
can do nothing.

00:43:49.350 --> 00:43:51.058
I mean, it has one
electron going around.

00:43:54.300 --> 00:43:56.169
I mean, the cooling
mostly comes from H2.

00:43:56.169 --> 00:43:58.460
So you have two electrons
because you have two protons,

00:43:58.460 --> 00:43:59.740
or HD.

00:43:59.740 --> 00:44:02.816
So it's a little bit
better than that.

00:44:02.816 --> 00:44:03.940
But you see the difference.

00:44:03.940 --> 00:44:06.870
So as soon as you have
even a few atoms in there,

00:44:06.870 --> 00:44:09.800
they radiate away, which
means they send out photons

00:44:09.800 --> 00:44:13.050
that can leave the gas cloud.

00:44:13.050 --> 00:44:14.580
And poof, your energy gone.

00:44:14.580 --> 00:44:18.107
So this is some critical
metallicity, so critical amount

00:44:18.107 --> 00:44:19.190
of elements that you need.

00:44:19.190 --> 00:44:24.700
It's very, very low, but really
it ushers in this transition.

00:44:34.072 --> 00:44:35.780
AUDIENCE: Please
correct me if I'm wrong,

00:44:35.780 --> 00:44:38.990
but I imagine that what
you see in the spectrum

00:44:38.990 --> 00:44:41.920
is basically determined
by the composition

00:44:41.920 --> 00:44:44.720
of the surface of the star.

00:44:44.720 --> 00:44:48.290
Do we know to what extent
that matches the distribution

00:44:48.290 --> 00:44:50.140
of elements in the whole star?

00:44:50.140 --> 00:44:51.990
ANNA FREBEL: Yeah,
that's a great question.

00:44:51.990 --> 00:44:53.290
And that's always the concern.

00:44:53.290 --> 00:44:54.790
So that's why we
have to make sure

00:44:54.790 --> 00:44:59.560
that we catch the stars in
the right evolutionary phase.

00:44:59.560 --> 00:45:03.400
To back up a little bit, people
have done for a long time--

00:45:03.400 --> 00:45:06.160
actually, that was the
beginning of astrophysics

00:45:06.160 --> 00:45:07.350
with a computer.

00:45:07.350 --> 00:45:10.430
They have calculated the
evolutionary paths of stars.

00:45:10.430 --> 00:45:11.750
So stars evolve.

00:45:11.750 --> 00:45:13.470
They get born.

00:45:13.470 --> 00:45:15.490
They start to burn
hydrogen to helium.

00:45:15.490 --> 00:45:18.540
Later on they burn helium
to heavier elements.

00:45:18.540 --> 00:45:20.430
And so there is a
whole sequence that

00:45:20.430 --> 00:45:24.260
also correlates to how the
star looks from the outside.

00:45:24.260 --> 00:45:25.120
It changes color.

00:45:25.120 --> 00:45:29.040
It changes size as a function
of what's going on inside.

00:45:29.040 --> 00:45:35.990
And so we know very well at
what time the star gets mixed

00:45:35.990 --> 00:45:39.190
and whether the outer
layers actually realize

00:45:39.190 --> 00:45:40.880
what's happening inside.

00:45:40.880 --> 00:45:44.170
So our stars, it's the
case that the outer layers

00:45:44.170 --> 00:45:46.730
don't realize at all what's
going on in the center

00:45:46.730 --> 00:45:48.490
because they are
just burning hydrogen

00:45:48.490 --> 00:45:49.507
to helium in the center.

00:45:49.507 --> 00:45:51.090
And the outer layers
really don't care

00:45:51.090 --> 00:45:52.390
at all what's happening there.

00:45:52.390 --> 00:45:56.040
They just sit there undisturbed
for billions of years because

00:45:56.040 --> 00:45:57.900
of their very slow evolution.

00:45:57.900 --> 00:46:00.830
If we had, let's
say, a 0.9 solar mass

00:46:00.830 --> 00:46:03.210
star, that would evolve faster.

00:46:03.210 --> 00:46:06.190
And if we would see it today,
it would still be alive,

00:46:06.190 --> 00:46:10.700
but it would have
already started

00:46:10.700 --> 00:46:12.900
to burn helium into carbon.

00:46:12.900 --> 00:46:15.430
And in the process of
that, the star gets mixed.

00:46:15.430 --> 00:46:19.270
And the carbon from the
interior gets indeed transported

00:46:19.270 --> 00:46:20.660
to the outer layers.

00:46:20.660 --> 00:46:22.350
So we call that self-enrichment.

00:46:22.350 --> 00:46:24.690
And that's also very
interesting to study.

00:46:24.690 --> 00:46:26.770
But for stellar
archaeology, that's

00:46:26.770 --> 00:46:30.850
a big no no because then
we can't transfer anymore

00:46:30.850 --> 00:46:34.410
what we see today to what
the composition was before.

00:46:40.090 --> 00:46:43.390
AUDIENCE: My sister-in-law was
a telescope driver at Kitt Peak.

00:46:43.390 --> 00:46:48.210
And often the scientists weren't
actually necessarily there.

00:46:48.210 --> 00:46:52.090
And I expect a lot of
times, as a scientist,

00:46:52.090 --> 00:46:55.110
you don't actually have to
ever get near the telescopes

00:46:55.110 --> 00:46:56.640
for these observations to occur.

00:46:56.640 --> 00:46:59.260
How frequently do you go?

00:46:59.260 --> 00:47:05.650
And do you go for practical
reasons, or just because it's--

00:47:05.650 --> 00:47:08.400
ANNA FREBEL: Well actually
all of the above, sort of.

00:47:08.400 --> 00:47:09.420
So it's true.

00:47:09.420 --> 00:47:12.990
Most telescopes these days
have professional operators.

00:47:12.990 --> 00:47:16.010
And the astronomer doesn't
even need to go there anymore.

00:47:16.010 --> 00:47:18.590
Certainly all of the big
ones except for the Magellan

00:47:18.590 --> 00:47:20.340
telescopes that I'm using.

00:47:20.340 --> 00:47:24.340
They have the old school policy
that if you want to take data,

00:47:24.340 --> 00:47:26.300
you've got to better
do it yourself.

00:47:26.300 --> 00:47:31.820
And for our discovery work,
that is actually very beneficial

00:47:31.820 --> 00:47:35.530
because I need to inspect the
data right there and right then

00:47:35.530 --> 00:47:37.694
because the stars
are not observable

00:47:37.694 --> 00:47:39.360
all night long because
they are standing

00:47:39.360 --> 00:47:40.800
steady above my telescope.

00:47:40.800 --> 00:47:41.910
They are moving.

00:47:41.910 --> 00:47:43.770
And if I want to keep
catching the star

00:47:43.770 --> 00:47:45.860
because it turned out to
be really interesting,

00:47:45.860 --> 00:47:48.020
so we take a quick
exposure first.

00:47:48.020 --> 00:47:52.470
And we inspect it because we
only deal with candidates.

00:47:52.470 --> 00:47:56.670
And so we then have to make
the decision, yea or nay.

00:47:56.670 --> 00:47:58.720
So that has to happen fast.

00:47:58.720 --> 00:48:01.310
If someone was to
take the data and then

00:48:01.310 --> 00:48:05.740
we would get it the next day,
and then we'll look at it.

00:48:05.740 --> 00:48:07.590
It might not be
observable anymore.

00:48:07.590 --> 00:48:09.400
The weather might turn bad.

00:48:09.400 --> 00:48:12.280
That kind of moment
just kind of goes.

00:48:12.280 --> 00:48:15.030
And so for us, it's very
good to be at the telescope

00:48:15.030 --> 00:48:19.010
and focus 100% percent
on that and get our data.

00:48:19.010 --> 00:48:23.610
Now I travel to Chile about
two or three times a year.

00:48:23.610 --> 00:48:25.310
It takes a long
time to get there,

00:48:25.310 --> 00:48:27.335
something like three hours.

00:48:27.335 --> 00:48:31.087
And I always feel like I
need a vacation coming back

00:48:31.087 --> 00:48:32.420
because you work all night long.

00:48:32.420 --> 00:48:37.850
You have to switch 12 hours,
working from days then nights.

00:48:37.850 --> 00:48:42.260
In between you have night
over flights down there.

00:48:42.260 --> 00:48:44.020
So that's no fun.

00:48:44.020 --> 00:48:45.780
But being there is a lot of fun.

00:48:45.780 --> 00:48:48.970
And then having the
data is a lot of fun.

00:48:48.970 --> 00:48:51.450
But I do really think that
it's important for at least

00:48:51.450 --> 00:48:53.270
every student to
go to a telescope

00:48:53.270 --> 00:48:55.250
once to see the process.

00:48:55.250 --> 00:48:57.800
But with all these
big new sky surveys,

00:48:57.800 --> 00:49:00.450
people just download the
data from the internet now.

00:49:00.450 --> 00:49:02.990
And I have come across
students who, A,

00:49:02.990 --> 00:49:06.000
don't think the data is real
because it was downloaded

00:49:06.000 --> 00:49:06.750
from the internet.

00:49:06.750 --> 00:49:07.610
It was like faked.

00:49:07.610 --> 00:49:09.890
Yeah sure, we can
make fake data.

00:49:09.890 --> 00:49:11.230
We have.

00:49:11.230 --> 00:49:12.530
That has certain purposes.

00:49:18.820 --> 00:49:23.980
As a scientist, your work
is based on data collection.

00:49:23.980 --> 00:49:27.484
And that has been
erased from astronomy.

00:49:27.484 --> 00:49:28.900
Downloading data
from the internet

00:49:28.900 --> 00:49:33.030
is not data collection,
at least not to me.

00:49:33.030 --> 00:49:36.670
So that's another
reason why I really

00:49:36.670 --> 00:49:38.790
enjoy going there
because it brings me back

00:49:38.790 --> 00:49:41.830
to the root of my profession
and one of the reasons

00:49:41.830 --> 00:49:44.220
why I wanted to become an
astronomer in the first place.

00:49:44.220 --> 00:49:46.560
And being on the mountain
top, and seeing the sun down,

00:49:46.560 --> 00:49:49.470
and having the mountains
that tinged in purple,

00:49:49.470 --> 00:49:51.420
and having the night
sky above me, I mean,

00:49:51.420 --> 00:49:53.090
that's just priceless
on top of that.

00:50:03.820 --> 00:50:06.550
AUDIENCE: So I noticed
you use heavier elements.

00:50:06.550 --> 00:50:09.950
You don't say metals.

00:50:09.950 --> 00:50:12.650
Is that because you're talking
to the public and astronomers

00:50:12.650 --> 00:50:14.502
have hydrogen, helium, and
then metals for everything

00:50:14.502 --> 00:50:15.140
else, right?

00:50:15.140 --> 00:50:17.280
ANNA FREBEL: I took
that slide out.

00:50:17.280 --> 00:50:19.520
I had to cut a few slides.

00:50:19.520 --> 00:50:21.399
You want me to elaborate, or--

00:50:21.399 --> 00:50:22.940
AUDIENCE: You go
into it in the book?

00:50:22.940 --> 00:50:25.170
ANNA FREBEL: Yes, I am.

00:50:25.170 --> 00:50:28.590
Because I do believe that
with sufficient explanation

00:50:28.590 --> 00:50:34.200
and motivation, the public can
understand a lot of details.

00:50:34.200 --> 00:50:35.790
You just got to
walk them through.

00:50:35.790 --> 00:50:40.260
So what we're talking about
is that astronomers are not

00:50:40.260 --> 00:50:43.600
chemists, so we can do
pretty much whatever we want.

00:50:43.600 --> 00:50:46.410
And the universe is a complex
and complicated place.

00:50:46.410 --> 00:50:48.770
So a long time ago,
someone came up

00:50:48.770 --> 00:50:54.070
with a grandiose idea of lumping
all the chemical elements

00:50:54.070 --> 00:50:55.580
into one thing.

00:50:55.580 --> 00:50:58.350
And so they're called hydrogen
because the universe is

00:50:58.350 --> 00:51:01.950
full of hydrogen, X. Then
helium is the second most common

00:51:01.950 --> 00:51:02.550
element.

00:51:02.550 --> 00:51:04.907
They called it Y. And
then all the rest,

00:51:04.907 --> 00:51:05.990
that's kind of negligible.

00:51:05.990 --> 00:51:10.440
That's Z. So if your
dinner conversation ever

00:51:10.440 --> 00:51:13.580
goes stale, just tell them,
what's the universe made of?

00:51:13.580 --> 00:51:16.460
XYZ, haha.

00:51:16.460 --> 00:51:19.420
So we look for the
stars with the least

00:51:19.420 --> 00:51:21.100
amount of heavy
elements in them,

00:51:21.100 --> 00:51:24.847
which means we look for stars
that are poor in metals,

00:51:24.847 --> 00:51:25.680
all of the elements.

00:51:25.680 --> 00:51:27.750
So we call them
metal poor stars.

00:51:27.750 --> 00:51:29.220
So that's the jargon.

00:51:29.220 --> 00:51:33.960
But usually unless I give a long
talk, so in my hour long talks

00:51:33.960 --> 00:51:35.340
I do it.

00:51:35.340 --> 00:51:38.020
But in the shorter ones
I usually cut it out.

00:51:38.020 --> 00:51:39.030
Thank you so much.

00:51:39.030 --> 00:51:42.390
[APPLAUSE]

